4 "§ 115D-4.1. College transfer program approval; standards for programs; annual
5 reporting requirements.
6 (a) Repealed by Session Laws 1995, c. 288, s. 1, effective September 1, 1995.
7 (b) The State Board of Community Colleges may approve the addition of the college
8 transfer program to a community college. If addition of the college transfer program to an
9 institution would require a substantial increase in funds, State Board approval shall be subject to
10 appropriation of funds by the General Assembly for this purpose.
11 (c) Addition of the college transfer program shall not decrease an institution's ability to
12 provide programs within its basic mission of vocational and technical training and basic academic
13 education.
14 (d) The State Board of Community Colleges shall develop appropriate criteria and
15 standards to regulate the addition of the college transfer program to institutions.
16 (e) The State Board of Community Colleges shall develop appropriate criteria and
17 standards to regulate the operation of college transfer programs.
18 (f) The Board of Governors of The University of North Carolina shall report to each
19 community college and to the State Board of Community Colleges in accordance with
20 G.S. 116-11(10b) on the academic performance of that community college's transfer students. If
21 the State Board of Community Colleges finds that college transfer students from a community
22 college are not consistently performing adequately at a four-year college, the Board shall review
23 the community college's program and determine what steps are necessary to remedy the problem.
24 The Board shall report annually to the General Assembly on the reports it receives and on what
25 steps it is taking to remedy problems that it finds.
26 (g) The Community Colleges System Office shall report by April 15, 2011, and annually
27 thereafter, to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee, the State Board of Education,
28 the Office of State Budget and Management, and the Fiscal Research Division of the General
29 Assembly on the implementation of the UNC-NCCCS 2+2 E-Learning Initiative. This report
30 shall include:
31 (1) The courses and programs within the 2+2 E-Learning Initiative;
32 (2) The total number of prospective teachers that have taken or are taking part in
33 this initiative to date broken down by the current academic period and each of
34 the previous academic periods since the program’s inception;
35 (3) The total number of teachers currently in the State’s classrooms, by local
36 school administrative unit, who have taken part in this initiative;
37 (4) The change in the number of teachers available to schools since the program’s
38 inception;
39 (5) The qualitative data from students, teachers, local school administrative unit
40 personnel, university personnel, and community college personnel as to the
41 impact of this initiative on our State’s teaching pool; and
42 (6) An explanation of the expenditures and collaborative programs between the
43 North Carolina Community College System and The University of North
44 Carolina, including recommendations for improvement.
45 "§ 115D-5. Administration of institutions by State Board of Community Colleges;
46 personnel exempt from North Carolina Human Resources Act; extension
47 courses; tuition waiver; in-plant training; contracting, etc., for establishment
48 and operation of extension units of the community college system; use of existing
49 public school facilities.
50 (a) The State Board of Community Colleges may adopt and execute such policies,
51 regulations and standards concerning the establishment, administration, and operation of
