6 (c) No course of instruction shall be offered by any community college at State expense
7 or partial State expense to any captive or co-opted group of students, as defined by the State
8 Board of Community Colleges, without prior approval of the State Board of Community
9 Colleges. All course offerings approved for State prison inmates or prisoners in local jails must
10 be tied to clearly identified job skills, transition needs, or both. Approval by the State Board of
11 Community Colleges shall be presumed to constitute approval of both the course and the group
12 served by that institution. The State Board of Community Colleges may delegate to the President
13 the power to make an initial approval, with final approval to be made by the State Board of
14 Community Colleges. A course taught without such approval will not yield any full-time
15 equivalent students, as defined by the State Board of Community Colleges.
16 (c1) Community colleges shall report full-time equivalent (FTE) student hours for
17 correction education programs on the basis of student membership hours. No community college
18 shall operate a multi-entry/multi-exit class or program in a prison facility, except for a literacy
19 class or program.
20 The State Board shall work with the Division of Adult Correction and Juvenile Justice of the
21 Department of Public Safety on offering classes and programs that match the average length of
22 stay of an inmate in a prison facility.
23 (c2) Courses in federal prisons shall not earn regular budget full-time equivalents, but may
24 be offered on a self-supporting basis.
25 (c3) Funds appropriated for community college courses for prison inmates shall be used
26 only for inmates in State prisons. The first priority for the use of these funds shall be to restore
27 the FTE for basic skills courses to the FY 2008-2009 level. Funds not needed for this purpose
28 may be used for continuing education and curriculum courses related to job skills training.
