21 "§ 115D-5.1. Workforce Development Programs.
22 (a) Community colleges shall assist in the preemployment and in-service training of
23 employees in industry, business, agriculture, health occupation and governmental agencies. Such
24 training shall include instruction on worker safety and health standards and practices applicable
25 to the field of employment. The State Board of Community Colleges shall make appropriate
26 regulations including the establishment of maximum hours of instruction which may be offered
27 at State expense in each in-plant training program. No instructor or other employee of a
28 community college shall engage in the normal management, supervisory and operational
29 functions of the establishment in which the instruction is offered during the hours in which the
30 instructor or other employee is employed for instructional or educational purposes.
31 (b) through (d) Repealed by Session Laws 2008-107, s. 8.7(a), effective July 1, 2008.
32 (e) There is created within the North Carolina Community College System the
33 Customized Training Program. The Customized Training Program shall offer programs and
34 training services to assist new and existing business and industry to remain productive, profitable,
35 and within the State. Before a business or industry qualifies to receive assistance under the
36 Customized Training Program, the President of the North Carolina Community College System
37 shall determine that:
38 (1) The business is making an appreciable capital investment;
39 (2) The business is deploying new technology;
40 (2a) The business or individual is creating jobs, expanding an existing workforce,
41 or enhancing the productivity and profitability of the operations within the
42 State; and
43 (3) The skills of the workers will be enhanced by the assistance.
44 (f) The Community Colleges System Office shall report no later than September 1 of
45 each year to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee on:
46 (1) The total amount of funds received by a company under the Customized
47 Training Program.
48 (1a) The types of services sought by the company, whether for new, expanding, or
49 existing industry.
50 (2) The amount of funds per trainee received by that company.
Senate Bill 125-First Edition Page 9

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) The amount of funds received per trainee by the community college delivering
2 the training.
3 (4) The number of trainees trained by the company and community college.
4 (5) The number of years that company has been funded.
5 (f1) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, the State Board of Community Colleges
6 may adopt guidelines that allow the Customized Training Program to use funds appropriated for
7 that program to support training projects for the various branches of the Armed Forces of the
8 United States.
9 (f2) Funds available to the Customized Training Program shall not revert at the end of a
10 fiscal year but shall remain available until expended. Up to ten percent (10%) of the
11 college-delivered training expenditures and up to five percent (5%) of the contractor-delivered
12 training expenditures for the prior fiscal year for Customized Training may be allotted to each
13 college for capacity building at that college.
14 (f3) Of the funds appropriated in a fiscal year for the Customized Training Programs, the
15 State Board of Community Colleges may approve the use of up to eight percent (8%) for the
16 training and support of regional community college personnel to deliver Customized Training
17 Program services to business and industry.
18 (g) The State Board shall adopt guidelines to implement this section. At least 20 days
19 before the effective date of any criteria or nontechnical amendments to guidelines, the State
20 Board must publish the proposed guidelines on the Community Colleges System Office's web
21 site and provide notice to persons who have requested notice of proposed guidelines. In addition,
22 the State Board must accept oral and written comments on the proposed guidelines during the 15
23 business days beginning on the first day that the State Board has completed these notifications.
24 For the purpose of this subsection, a technical amendment is either of the following:
25 (1) An amendment that corrects a spelling or grammatical error.
26 (2) An amendment that makes a clarification based on public comment and could
27 have been anticipated by the public notice that immediately preceded the
28 public comment.
29 "§ 115D-5.1A. Short-Term Workforce Development Grant Program.
30 (a) Program Established. – There is established the North Carolina Community College
31 Short-Term Workforce Development Grant Program (Program) to be administered by the State
32 Board of Community Colleges. The State Board shall adopt rules for the disbursement of the
33 grants pursuant to this section.
34 (b) Programs of Study. – The State Board of Community Colleges, in collaboration with
35 the Department of Commerce, shall determine the eligible programs of study for the Program,
36 according to the occupations that are in the highest demand in the State. The eligible programs
37 of study shall include programs such as architecture and construction, health sciences,
38 information technology, electrical line worker, and manufacturing programs and may include
39 other programs to meet local workforce needs.
40 (c) Award Amounts. – To the extent funds are made available for the Program, the State
41 Board of Community Colleges shall award grants in an amount of up to seven hundred fifty
42 dollars ($750.00) to students pursuing short-term, noncredit State and industry workforce
43 credentials. The State Board of Community Colleges shall establish criteria for initial and
44 continuing eligibility for students. At a minimum, students shall be required to qualify as a
45 resident for tuition purposes under the criteria set forth in G.S. 116-143.1 and in accordance with
46 the coordinated and centralized residency determination process administered by the State
47 Education Assistance Authority.
48 (d) Report. – The State Board shall submit a report by April 1, 2024, and annually
49 thereafter, on the Program to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee and the Fiscal
50 Research Division. The report shall contain, for each academic year and by programs of study,
51 the amount of grant funds disbursed and the number of eligible students receiving funds.
