13 "§ 115D-6. Withdrawal of State support.
14 The State Board of Community Colleges may withdraw or withhold State financial and
15 administrative support of any institutions subject to the provisions of this Chapter in the event
16 that:of any of the following:
17 (1) The required local financial support of an institution is not provided;provided.
18 (2) Sufficient State funds are not available;available.
19 (3) The officials of an institution refuse or are unable to maintain prescribed
20 standards of administration or instruction; orinstruction.
21 (4) Local educational needs for such an institution cease to exist.
22 "§ 115D-6.1. Administration of institutions.
23 (a) Policies. – The State Board of Community Colleges may adopt and execute such
24 policies, regulations, and standards concerning the establishment, administration, and operation
25 of institutions as the State Board may deem necessary to ensure the quality of educational
26 programs, to promote the systematic meeting of educational needs of the State, and to provide
27 for the equitable distribution of State and federal funds to the several institutions.
28 (b) Authority. – The State Board shall have the following authority with respect to
29 individual institutions:
30 (1) To approve sites, capital improvement projects, and budgets.
31 (2) To approve the selection of the chief administrative officer.
32 (3) To establish and administer standards for professional personnel, curricula,
33 admissions, and graduation.
34 (4) To regulate the awarding of degrees, diplomas, and certificates.
35 (5) To establish and regulate student tuition and fees within policies for tuition
36 and fees established by the General Assembly.
37 (6) To establish and regulate financial accounting procedures.
38 (c) Salaries. – The State Board shall establish standards and scales for salaries and
39 allotments paid from funds administered by the State Board, and all employees of the institutions
40 shall be exempt from the provisions of the North Carolina Human Resources Act. Any and all
41 salary caps set by the State Board for community college presidents shall apply only to the
42 State-paid portion of the salary. Except as otherwise provided by law, the employer contribution
43 rate on the local-paid portion of the salary, to be paid from local funds, shall be set by the State
44 Treasurer based on actuarial recommendations.
45 (d) Faculty Credentials. – The State Board of Community Colleges shall require each
46 community college to meet the faculty credential requirements of its accrediting agency for all
47 community college programs.
48 "§ 115D-6.2. Accreditation.Accreditation policy.
49 The State Board of Community Colleges shall adopt a policy requiring community colleges
50 to be accredited in accordance with G.S. 115D-21.2.
51 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
Senate Bill 125-First Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Accreditation cycle. – The period of time during which a community college
2 is accredited.
3 (2) Accrediting agency. – An agency or association that accredits institutions of
4 higher education.
5 (3) Regional accrediting agency. – One of the following accrediting agencies:
6 a. Higher Learning Commission.
7 b. Middle States Commission on Higher Education.
8 c. New England Commission on Higher Education.
9 d. Northwest Commission on Colleges and Universities.
10 e. Southern Association of Colleges and Schools Commission on
11 Colleges.
12 f. Western Association of Schools and Colleges Accrediting
13 Commission for Community and Junior Colleges.
14 (b) Prohibit Consecutive Accreditation by an Accrediting Agency. – A community
15 college shall not receive accreditation by an accrediting agency for consecutive accreditation
16 cycles except as provided in subsection (c) of this section.
17 (c) Accreditation Transfer Procedure. – A community college that pursues accreditation
18 with a different accrediting agency in accordance with this section shall pursue accreditation with
19 a regional accrediting agency. If the community college is not granted candidacy status by any
20 regional accrediting agency that is different from its current accrediting agency at least three
21 years prior to the expiration of its current accreditation, the community college may remain with
22 its current accrediting agency for an additional accreditation cycle.
23 (d) Certain Programs Exempt. – The requirements of this section do not apply to
24 professional, departmental, or certificate programs at community colleges that have specific
25 accreditation requirements or best practices, as identified by the State Board of Community
26 Colleges.
27 (e) Cause of Action. – A community college may bring a civil action, as follows:
28 (1) Against any person who makes a false statement to the accrediting agency of
29 the community college, if all of the following criteria are met:
30 a. The statement, if true, would mean the community college is out of
31 compliance with its accreditation standards.
32 b. The person made the statement with knowledge that the statement was
33 false or with reckless disregard as to whether it was false.
34 c. The accrediting agency conducted a review of the community college
35 as a proximate result of the statement.
36 d. The review caused the community college to incur costs.
37 (2) A community college that prevails on a cause of action initiated pursuant to
38 this subsection shall be entitled to the following:
39 a. Costs related to the review conducted by the accrediting agency,
40 including for the following:
41 1. Additional hours worked by community college personnel.
42 2. Contracted services, including outside legal counsel.
43 3. Travel, lodging, and food expenses.
44 4. Fees required by the agency.
45 b. Reasonable attorney fees.
46 c. Court costs.
