8 "§ 115D-10.21. Training programs for students with intellectual and developmental
9 disabilities.
10 (a) The State Board of Community Colleges shall establish a community college training
11 program for up to 15 community colleges. The program shall provide opportunities for
12 micro-credentials or other credentials that lead to increased employment outcomes for
13 individuals with intellectual and developmental disabilities (IDD). To the extent funds are
14 appropriated for this purpose, the program shall improve the ability of participating community
15 colleges to offer training and educational components that include improving employability skills
16 and providing on-the-job training and apprenticeships with business and industry for individuals
17 with IDD. The goal of the program shall be to inform community colleges and address
18 cross-departmental supports within the individual community colleges on programs for
19 individuals with IDD related to at least the following:
20 (1) Establishing best practices for providing vocational training for individuals
21 with IDD.
22 (2) Providing financial and benefits counseling.
23 (3) Developing strategies on integrating assistive technology.
24 (4) Maximizing access, with supports, to credential and degree programs,
25 including micro-credentials that are established by the State Board.
26 (5) Identifying methods to increase orientation and integration of individuals with
27 IDD into the college community to the greatest extent possible.
28 (6) Determining a needs assessment, marketing, and evaluation to serve a broad
29 array of individuals with developmental and other similar disabilities or
30 learning challenges to assure adequate demand for new or existing programs.
31 (b) No later than May 1 of each year, the Community Colleges System Office shall report
32 on the funds appropriated to the System Office for the purposes of this section to the Joint
33 Legislative Education Oversight Committee and the Fiscal Research Division. At a minimum,
34 the report shall address the impact of the program, the use of any additional positions created at
35 community colleges, professional development training for staff, and funding sources identified
36 for individuals with IDD to build programs at community colleges that support postsecondary
37 trainings and certifications that enable individuals with IDD to engage in competitive, sustainable
38 employment.
